<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" dir="ltr">

<head>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="CSS/style.css">
	<link href="/vendor/fontawesome/css/all.css" rel="stylesheet">

	<title>Graph it!</title>
	<script src="JS/Math/Vector2.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Math/Matrix3.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Application/Application.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Graphics/Color.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Graphics/Canvas.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Graphics/Graph.js"></script>
	<script src="JS/Main.js"></script>
</head>

<body>
	<aside class="noselect">
		<div id="asideWrapper">
			<nav class="noselect">
				<i class="fas fa-arrow-alt-circle-left option" id="inputToggle"></i>
				<i class="fas fa-info option" id="infoToggle"></i>
			</nav>

			<div id="inputWrapper">
				<textarea id="functions" placeholder="Write expressions to be rendered here"></textarea>
				<textarea id="variables" placeholder="Write constants here"></textarea>
				<textarea id="userFunctions" placeholder="Write functions here"></textarea>
			</div>
			
			<div id="info">
				Input functions in the expression area using the following format for lines: y=value, x=value and the following for points: (value, value) or (value)<br><br>You can also graph derivitives by typing y='value or x='value, you can also reference other functions for example:<ul><li>y = xx</li><li>y = 'y0</li></ul> will create one function rendering x*x and another one rendering the derivitive of that function<br><br>You have access to functions like: sin, cos, tan, etc<br><br>You also have access to t, which starts at 0 when page is loaded and goes up over time<br><br>You can also create your own constants in the constants area using the following format: type name = value, the constants will be defined in the order they are written, you have access to all previous mentioned functions and constants<br><br>You can restrict a line to a certain area, for example:
				<ul>
					<li>y=xx {y>1;y<3;x>0}</li>
				</ul>
				You can also define your own functions in the functions area, for example:
				<ul>
					<li>function float c(float a, float b) { return a + b; }</li>
				</ul>
				You can then access this in your expressions, like this:
				<ul>
					<li>y = c(1, 2)</li>
				</ul>
				You can move around the graph using left click and zoom in/out using the mousewheel<br><br>Examples of expressions:
				<ul>
					<li>y = 2xx</li>
					<li>y = '2xx</li>
					<li>(sin(t), cos(t))</li>
				</ul>
				Examples of constants:
				<ul>
					<li>float PI = 3.14159265359</li>
					<li>float e = 2.71828</li>
					<li>float otherConstant = PI * e</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</aside>
</body>

</html>